> This vibrant veggie recipe is loosely based on a traditional Dutch stamppot. Though there isn't a perfect equivalent in English, the word stamppot roughly translates to hotchpotch—a fitting name for this busy yet delicious dish.

Preheat the oven to 220°C/200°C fan/gas mark 7. Boil a large #pot of water.

Chop half the @potatoes{200%g} and all the @sweet potatoes{300%g} into 2cm chunks.

Add sweet potatoes, chopped potatoes and @vegetable stock{1%sachet} to boiling water 
and cook until fork tender, ~{15-20%minutes}.

Once cooked, drain and return to the pot off the heat. Add a knob of @butter{1%knob} 
and some @?water{to taste} or @?milk{to taste}. Mash with a #potato masher{} until smooth, 
season to taste with @salt{to taste} and @pepper{to taste} and cover to keep warm.

Meanwhile, quarter the @tomatoes{2}.

On a lined #baking tray{}, mix the tomato with @balsamic vinegar{1%sachet}.

Season with salt and pepper.

Bake in the oven for ~{10-15%minutes}.

Meanwhile, place a medium #pan over high heat (no oil).

Once hot, toast the @walnuts{20%g} for ~{1-2%minutes}, shifting constantly,
until golden brown. Remove from pan and keep aside.

Halve, peel and slice the @onion{1}.

Return the (now empty) pan to medium-high heat with a drizzle of @oil{to taste}.

Once hot fry the onion until softened, ~{6-8%minutes}.

Season with salt and pepper.

Mix the onion, @mustard{1%sachet}, half the @italian herbs{1/2%sachet} and half the 
@greek style cheese{100%g} into the pot with the mash.

Place over a medium heat, and warm until the cheese has melted.

Mix in the roast tomato and @salad leaves{40%g}.

Season to taste with salt and pepper.

Divide the mash between plates.

Garnish with the remaining cheese.

Finish with a sprinkling of walnut pieces.

> You can add milk optionally when mashing for a creamier texture.